  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I completely delete all Adobe CS6 files on my Mac?",
  "response": "To completely delete all Adobe CS6 files from your Mac, you\u2019ll need to uninstall the software and remove any associated files that may be left behind. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide:\n\n### Step 1: Uninstall Adobe CS6\n\n1. **Close all Adobe applications**: Ensure that all Adobe programs are closed before proceeding with the uninstallation.\n\n2. **Open Adobe Creative Suite Uninstaller**:\n   - Navigate to the Applications folder.\n   - Open the `Adobe Creative Suite 6` folder.\n   - Locate and launch the `Uninstall Adobe Creative Suite 6` application.\n\n3. **Follow the uninstallation prompts**: The uninstaller will guide you through the process. Follow the prompts to remove the applications.\n\n### Step 2: Remove Remaining Files\n\nEven after uninstalling, some files may remain. Follow these steps to locate and delete them:\n\n1. **Open Finder**: Click on Finder from the dock.\n\n2. **Go to the Library folder**:\n   - Press **Command + Shift + G** to open the \u201cGo to Folder\u201d dialog.\n   - Type `~/Library` and hit Enter.\n\n3. **Search for Adobe-related files**:\n   - In the Library folder, check the following locations and delete Adobe-related folders or files if they exist:\n     - `Application Support/Adobe`\n     - `Preferences/com.adobe.*` (files starting with \"com.adobe\")\n     - `Caches/Adobe`\n     - `Logs/Adobe`\n     - `LaunchAgents`, `LaunchDaemons`, and `Preferences` (inside these folders, look for anything Adobe-related)\n   \n4. **Check System Library (optional but thorough)**:\n   - Open the \u201cGo to Folder\u201d dialog again and type in `/Library` (without the tilde).\n   - Look in Google the same folders as above (`Application Support`, `Caches`, `Preferences`, etc.) and delete any remaining Adobe files.\n\n### Step 3: Empty the Trash\n\n1. **Empty your Trash**: After deleting the files, make sure to empty your Trash to permanently remove them from your Mac.\n\n### Step 4: Restart Your Mac\n\n1. **Restart your Mac**: This helps to ensure that all changes take effect and frees up any system resources previously used by Adobe applications.\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Backup Important Files**: Before deleting files, ensure that you have backups of any important projects or presets you may need.\n- **Use Third-Party Uninstallers**: If you\u2019re not comfortable manually searching for files, you can consider using third-party applications like AppCleaner or CleanMyMac, which can help find and remove leftover application files.\n\nFollowing these steps should effectively remove all Adobe CS6 files from your Mac.",
